# TESS Program G06185

Title: Nodal Precession Of Hot Jupiters - Combining Kepler And TESS To Probe Stellar Structure

PI: Stephan, Alexander - Ohio State University

Type: SMALL

Summary: Observing the nodal precession of Hot Jupiters (HJs) is a powerful and unique tool to study the interiors of hot, rapidly spinning stars. The upcoming TESS cycle presents a special opportunity to significantly increase the number of observed precessing HJs, as cycle 6 will cover the original KEPLER field. We propose to observe 41 hot target stars with TESS that have confirmed transiting HJs observed by KEPLER in order to measure their orbital precession speeds and stellar J2 values. By combining KEPLER archival data and new TESS observations we create one of the longest possible observational baselines of up to 14 years, highlighting TESS's importance for the long-term study of continuously evolving stellar and planetary systems.
